<TEXT>
In the political Tempest that has been the impeachment process, there are
several careers that have been changed forever.
One of those belongs to Dennis Hastert of Illinois.
Come January he'll have one of the most powerful jobs in the U.S.
government when he's the new speaker of the house.
Dennis Hastert, who will soon be 57, was a high school teacher and a
Wrestling coach before he was a politician.
<TURN>
Speaker Gingrich, myself and many other members of Congress --
<TURN>
<ANNOTATION> Reporter: </ANNOTATION>
He represents the largely republican suburbs west of Chicago.
He was a state legislator before he ran for Congress in 1986.
He is described as a conservative, but not an ideologue.
<TURN>
There's a big role to play.
We need to heal the wounds and we need to reach out across the aisle.
<TURN>
<ANNOTATION> Reporter: </ANNOTATION>
Hastert has risen quite high in republican ranks while keeping a
Fairly low profile.
<TURN>
I didn't really seek this at all.
It just kind of happened.
<TURN>
<ANNOTATION> Reporter: </ANNOTATION>
So far, at least, a man without obvious enemies.
</TEXT>
